\n* ''[[Habba]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[Mangalyam Tantunanena|MangalyamTantunanena]]'' (1998)\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|2560181|Ravi Babu}}\n\n{{Ravi Babu}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Babu, Ravi}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Telugu male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Kannada cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Tamil cinema]]\n[[Category:Telugu film directors]]\n[[Category:Telugu screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Moorlord15", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDirector, writer and producer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ravi_Babu"}
{"title_page": "Rodney Howard-Browne", "text_new": "{{short description|South African preacher}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Rodney Howard-Browne\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = Rodney Morgan Howard Browne<ref name=\"TORONTOBLESSING\">{{Cite web|url=http://jbeard.users.rapidnet.com/bdm/Psychology/holylaugh.htm|title=Holy Laughter - Rodney Howard-Browne and the Toronto Blessing|website=jbeard.users.rapidnet.com|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1961|6|12}}<ref name=\"TORONTOBLESSING\"></ref>\n|birth_place   = [[Port Elizabeth]], South Africa\n|residence=[[Tampa, Florida]], U.S.\n|nationality   = South African\n|spouse        = Adonica Howard-Browne (nee Weyers)\n|website       = [http://www.revival.com Revival Ministries International]\n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Rodney (Morgan) Howard-Browne''' (born June 12, 1961)<ref name=\"HCDC\">{{cite web |title=Hernando County Inmate Booking Information: Rodney Howard Browne |url=https://www.hernandosheriff.org/jail/Applications/JailSearch/JailSearchDetails.aspx?BookNo=HCSO20JBN002084 |website=Hernando County Detention Center |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> is a South African-born American Christian [[Evangelism|evangelist]] and pastor of The River church in Tampa Bay.  He has resided in [[Tampa]], [[Florida]] since the mid-1990s. The River is considered both [[Pentecostal]] and [[Charismatic]] with [[revival meetings]], led by Howard-Browne, known for those in the audience breaking into \"[[holy laughter]]\".<ref name=\"TBT\"/><ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=ravitz/><ref name=\"VOA\"/>  Howard-Browne is the head of Revival Ministries International, a group he and his wife founded in 1997.\n\n==Biography==\nHoward-Browne and his three brothers (Mervyn, Bazil, and Gil) were raised in a [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] family in the cities of [[Port Elizabeth]] and [[East London, Eastern Cape|East London]], South Africa. His father, Frank Mervyn Derric Howard-Browne (1924\u20132005),<ref name=\"TBT090205\">{{cite news |title=Frank Howard-Browne Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tampabaytimes/obituary.aspx?n=frank-howard-browne&pid=15005170 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=September 2, 2005}}</ref> was a cleric.  Howard-Browne became a Christian at age five.<ref name=\"M&G\"/> In 1981, he met and married his wife Adonica (n\u00e9e Weyers).<ref name=ravitz>Ravitz, Jessica. [https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=5294497&itype=NGPSID \"Up for Godly giddiness: Pastor spreads the joy of salvation 'anywhere the Lord opens a door.'\"] The Salt Lake Tribune, March 22, 2007</ref> In the 1980s, he volunteered to work for [[Youth for Christ]] before doing a teaching stint with Rhema Bible School in [[Johannesburg]].\n\nIn December 1989, the family emigrated from South Africa to the United States,<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week251/profile.html \"Profile: Evangelist Rodney Howard-Browne.\"] Religion and Ethics NewsWeekly, PBS, August 20, 1999</ref><ref name=\"M&G\">{{cite news |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-03-16-gods-bartender-in-good-spirits|last1=Philp |first1=Rowan Philp |title=God's bartender in good spirits |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Mail & Guardian]] |date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> settling in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], and in 1991, he began holding revival meetings.<ref name=\"TBT090205\"/><ref name=\"Time062401\"/><ref name=\"RMI1\">{{cite web |title=History of Campmeetings |url=https://www.revival.com/index.html |website=Revival Ministries International |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |quote=Through the summer of 1991, we held revival meetings in Louisville, Kentucky, and all over the surrounding\u2026}}</ref> The Rodney Howard-Browne Evangelistic Association was incorporated in November 1993<ref name=\"FDS\">{{cite web |title=Rodney Howard Brown Evangelistic Association, Inc.: Annual Report 1994 |url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/ConvertTiffToPDF?storagePath=COR%5C0107%5C0105%5CAR000589.tif&documentNumber=F93000005142 |publisher=Florida Department of State, Division of Corporations |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref> and the family moved to the [[Tampa Bay, Florida]] area in 1994. Rodney's eldest brother Gil<ref name=\"TBT090205\"/> went on to operate Times of Refreshing Ministries, an online evangelical ministry.<ref name=\"TORM\">{{cite web |title=Times of Refreshing Ministries:The Internet Ministry of Evangelists Gil & Loraine Howard-Browne \u2013 About Us |url=http://revivaltimes.com/about.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref>. Likewise, his youngest brother Bazil established an eponymous evangelical ministry on 1 January 1994 with the professed aim of people achieving financial freedom through the special anointing of God <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bhbem.wordpress.com/2009/05/26/what-you-need-to-know-about-bazil-howard-browne/|title=What you need to know about Bazil Howard-Browne|date=May 26, 2009|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>. Prior to this he had worked alongside his brother Rodney for a year.\n\nIn 1996, Howard-Browne founded a church he named \"The River\" at Tampa Bay Church in [[Tampa, Florida]], serving as its pastor ever since.<ref name=\"TBT011005\">{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=Kevin |title=Church's Hummer prize too worldly? |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/01/10/Hillsborough/Church_s_Hummer_prize.shtml |accessdate=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=January 10, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326000430/http://www.sptimes.com/2005/01/10/Hillsborough/Church_s_Hummer_prize.shtml |archivedate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> Howard-Browne and his wife also founded Revival Ministries International in 1997, as well as River Bible Institute and River School of Worship.<ref>Howard-Browne, Rodney [https://www.revival.com/about \"About us\"] Revival.com</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne\u2019s services are characterized by [[faith healing|laying on of hands]] with worshipers giggling in apparent [[spiritual drunkenness]], [[speaking in tongues]], emitting animal noises, breaking into uncontrollable [[holy laughter]], shaking, dancing in the aisles, or falling to the ground.<ref name=\"TBT\"/><ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=ravitz/><ref name=\"VOA\">{{cite news |last1=Socolovsky |first1=Jerome |title=African-born Pastor Brings \u2018Holy Laughter\u2019 Revival to Washington |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/african-born-pastor-brings-holy-laughter-revival-to-washington/1954365.html|accessdate=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Voice of America]] |date=July 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"NunNews\">{{cite news |last1=Rohner |first1=Thomas |title=Conspiracy-theorizing megachurch preacher visits Nunavut|url=https://nunatsiaq.com/stories/article/conspiracy-theorizing-megachurch-preacher-visits-nunavut/ |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Nunatsiaq News]] |date=September 5, 2019 |quote=Howard-Browne also spoke in tongues, which he claimed was once understood in the obscure native dialect of a Papua New Guinea pastor}}</ref> He refers to himself as \"God's bartender\" and the \"holy ghost bartender\".<ref name=\"carnes\">Carnes, Tony. [http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/1999/august9/9t913a.html \"Howard-Browne Takes New York.\"] Christianity Today, August 9, 1999</ref><ref name=\"TBT\">{{cite news|url=http://tampabayonline.net/reports/minister/homealt.htm|title=The Holy Ghost Bartender|last=Bearden|first=Michelle|date=1999-06-28|newspaper=[[The Tampa Tribune]]|accessdate=2019-02-23|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707031815/http://tampabayonline.net/reports/minister/homealt.htm|archivedate=2012-07-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne is credited with introducing holy laughter to [[Carpenter's Home Church]] in [[Lakeland, Florida]] during a series of revival services with Karl Strader in 1993. The holy laughter revivals later spread to nearby churches in Melbourne, Titusville, Stuart and Vero Beach, Florida.<ref name=\"OS090196\">{{cite news |last1=Pinsky |first1=Mark I |title=When Holy Laughter Starts, Some Find It Hard To Stop |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1996-09-01-9608310934-story.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 1, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Ledger051808\">{{cite news |last1=McMullen |first1=Cary |title=Florida Outpouring: Internet Draws Thousands to Lakeland Revival |url= https://www.theledger.com/article/LK/20080518/News/608117817/LL/ |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[The Ledger]] |date=May 18, 2008}}</ref> Howard-Browne is credited with bringing holy laughter to the charismatic Toronto Airport Vineyard Church (soon after expelled by its parent [[Association of Vineyard Churches|Vineyard Church]]) at a 1994 revival in [[Toronto, Canada]] with evangelist Randy Clark, known as the \u201c[[Toronto Blessing]],\" and then a year later, to [[Assemblies of God]] (AOG) Brownsville Church in [[Pensacola, Florida]] with evangelist [[Steve Hill (evangelist)|Steve Hill]].  The event became known in Christian circles as the [[Brownsville Revival]].<ref name=\"OS090196\"/><ref name=\"Ledger051808\"/><ref name=\"Time062401\">{{cite news |last1=Ostling |first1=Richard N |title=Laughing for the Lord |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,164903,00.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Time Magazine]] |date=June 24, 2001}}</ref> Howard-Browne also ministered under pastor Mike Rose at the Juneau Christian Center (formerly known as the Bethel Assembly of God) in [[Juneau, Alaska]], an AOG church that [[Sarah Palin]] later attended after becoming governor of Alaska.<ref name=\"HuffPo101208\">{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Bruce |title=Palin and the Holy Laughter Anointing |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/palin-and-the-holy-laught_b_125582 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Huffington Post]] |date=October 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR090508\">{{cite news |last1=Bradley Hagerty |first1=Barbara |title=Examining Palin's Pentecostal Background |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=94332540 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=September 5, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Hapers083008\">{{cite news |last1=Silverstein |first1=Ken |title=Palin and Her Pastors: \"Those that die without Christ have a horrible, horrible surprise\" |url=https://harpers.org/blog/2008/08/palin-and-her-pastors-those-that-die-without-christ-have-a-horrible-horrible-surprise/ |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Harper's Magazine]] |date=August 30, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek102708\">{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Lisa |title=What Are Sarah Palin\u2019s Religious Beliefs? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/what-are-sarah-palins-religious-beliefs-91785 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |date=October 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne first came to national prominence in the US in 1999 when his Revival Ministries organization rented [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City for six weeks. The event, called Good News New York, was described as \u201can effort to achieve a Billy Graham-style faith uprising\u201d, but was \u201cderided in local media as a giant flop\u201d. It was estimated to cost up to $10 million but only 3,000 people were counted in attendance at the 19,000-seat arena.<ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=\"TBT\"/> Investigative journalists in his home town of Tampa reported at the time that since arriving from South Africa almost penniless in December 1989, his sudden wealth included a boat, a [[Harley Davidson]] motorcycle, a home in one of Tampa\u2019s exclusive gated communities and access to a private jet; however, they were unable to find evidence of financial wrongdoing.<ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"TBT\"/>\n\nHoward-Browne\u2019s daughter Kelly died due to cystic fibrosis on Christmas Day, 25 December 2002, at the age of 18. He then vowed that \u201csince the devil has taken their daughter with this dreaded disease, he would pay with one million souls over the next ten years\u201d.<ref name=\"Kambulow\"/><ref name=\"TBT122802\">{{cite news |title=Kelly Howard-Browne Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tampabaytimes/obituary.aspx?n=kelly-howard-browne&pid=680575 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=December 28, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, it was reported that Howard-Browne\u2019s River Church had hosted political meetings for the Florida chapter of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] during the preceding two years, including a rally for then presidential candidate [[Newt Gingrich]], at which Howard-Browne called for a national \"rising\" of Christian Americans \"that will not sit idly by and allow the killing of unborn babies and allow Islam to take over this country\". At the same event, he described [[Mormonism]] as a \"cult\" that, in the 19th century, \"had death squads that would go around killing everybody that was not a Mormon\". He later recanted, saying Mormons were \"honourable people\".<ref name=\"M&G\"/>\n\nHoward-Browne published ''The Killing of Uncle Sam: The Demise of the United States of America'', which was scheduled to be released in May 2018, and announced that proceeds from sales of the book would go to the River School of Government, a degree granting program, operated by Howard-Browne and his wife under the auspices of Revival Ministries, that funds training for people seeking to run for political office.<ref name=\"DFP\">{{cite news |last1=McGregor |first1=Grady |title=Controversial pastor visits Dickinson: Rival pastor from Montana dragged from church after protesting |url=https://www.thedickinsonpress.com/news/4360976-controversial-pastor-visits-dickinson-rival-pastor-montana-dragged-church-after |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Dickinson Press]] |date=November 17, 2017}}</ref>  \n\nHoward-Browne's evangelical movement has been rejected as cult-like by many mainstream Christian organisations, and it has been described as \"a combination of brimstone and fire about God\u2019s power, sprinkled with hipster references and a conviction that church\u2014like Disneyland\u2014should be 'the happiest place on earth'.\"<ref name=\"M&G\"/> The Christian Research Institute labelled his operation a \u201ccult\u201d and called the him \"a good stage hypnotist\" who has made millions from vulnerable believers.<ref name=\"M&G\"/> According to ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]'', critics have described him as \"a manipulator leading followers into a cult; a circus ring leader making a good living.\"<ref name=\"TBT\"/>\n\n==Statements and controversies==\n===Diploma mill doctorate===\nHoward-Browne claimed to have earned a \"doctorate of ministry degree\" in 1992  from \"The School of Bible Theology\", a [[non-accredited]] Pentecostal correspondence school in San Jacinto, California that has been described as a \"[[diploma mill]]\".<ref name=TBT/><ref name=\"AI1\">{{cite news|last1=Kowalski|first1=David|title=\"Name it and Frame it\" \u2014 Phony Doctorates in the Church|url=http://www.apologeticsindex.org/2794-name-it-and-frame-it-phony-doctorates-in-the-church|accessdate=May 3, 2018|publisher=Apologetics Index|date=2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dSur1KLjWIUC&source=gbs_navlinks_s|last1=Stokes |first1=Jerry |title=Joseph Smith and Word of Faith Movement |page=21 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Kambulow\">{{cite book |last1=Kambulow |first1=Walter |title=The Best of the Kambulows |date=June 1, 2003 |page=879 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/THE_BEST_OF_THE_KAMBULOW.html?id=YS3cAgAAQBAJ |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Multi-level marketing: Monavie and Jeunesse===\nHoward-Browne and his wife Adonica were top-ranking (\u201cBlack Diamond executive level\u201d) distributors for [[Monavie]], a [[multi-level marketing]] company that sold [[acai berry]] juice-based beverages until folding in 2014 subsequent to a $182 million loan default and allegations of [[pyramid scheme|pyramid scheming]], fraudulent advertising, and [[patent infringement]].<ref>{{cite web |title=MV Three Sixty Five Magazine |url=https://www.team-legacy.info/PDF/MV365_Magazine.pdf |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |pages=86}}</ref><ref name=\"YT\">{{cite news|title=Rodney and Adonica Howard-Browne MonaVie Black Diamond|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdXhteTaPpE|accessdate=May 2, 2018|agency=YouTube|publisher=[[Monavie|Monavie Corporate]]|date=March 18, 2009}}</ref><ref name=imagenetixdocket>{{cite web| title = Imagenetix, Inc. vs. Monavie LLC et al. | publisher = [[United States District Court]] for the Southern District of California | date = May 2, 2018 | url = https://ia800205.us.archive.org/20/items/gov.uscourts.casd.269686/gov.uscourts.casd.269686.1.0.pdf| accessdate = 2008-09-20}}</ref> As of 2016, Howard-Browne also served as a \"North America Emerald Director\" for the multi-level marketing company Jeunesse.<ref name=\"Jeunesse\">{{cite web |title=Legacy Powered by Jeunesse |url=https://www.team-legacy.com/PDF/OurTeam-OurProducts.pdf |publisher=Jeunesse Global Holdings, LLC |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |page=41 |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Allegation of plot to attack Donald Trump ===\nIn July 2017, Howard-Browne was one of 17 evangelical pastors who visited the [[White House]] to pray for and [[laying on of hands|lay hands]] on President [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"KCS\">{{cite news|last1=Gutierrez|first1=Lisa|title=\u2018Great spiritual awakening\u2019: Pastors lay hands on Donald Trump in the Oval Office|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/nation-world/article160904779.html|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=July 12, 2017}}</ref> In a video several days later, Howard-Browne stated that \u201cthere is a planned attack on our president and that\u2019s all I can tell you about right now; I know what I\u2019m talking about, I\u2019ve spoken to high-ranking people in the government\".<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-prayed-over-trump-in-order-to-avert-a-planned-attack-on-our-president/\n | title = Rodney Howard-Browne Prayed Over Trump In Order To Avert \u2018A Planned Attack On Our President\u2019 \n | last = Mantyla\n | first = Kyle\n | date = July 17, 2017\n | website = Right Wing Watch\n | publisher = People for the American Way\n | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = There is a planned attack on our president,\" he said, \u201cand that\u2019s all I can tell you about right now; I know what I\u2019m talking about, I\u2019ve spoken to high-ranking people in the government and this is being planned by people that hate God, hate America, hate our president and we have to stop this, in Jesus name.\u201d}}</ref> Howard-Browne later said that the Secret Service met with him to discover which congressman told him about the plot but he refused to say, citing pastoral privilege.<ref>\n {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/its-not-my-problem-rodney-howard-browne-refused-to-provide-the-secret-service-with-details-of-a-plot-again-trump/\n  | title = Pastor Who Claimed His Prayers Averted Anti-Trump Attack Refuses To Provide Details To Secret Service Because It\u2019s \u2018Not My Problem\u2019\n  | last = Mantyla\n  | first = Kyle\n  | date = July 31, 2017\n  | website = Right Wing Watch\n  | publisher = Right Wing Watch\n  | access-date = 21 December 2017\n | quote = Somebody reported me to the Secret Service, so they came over\u201d he claimed. \u201cThree guys, we sat and talked; very nice people and they wanted to know who the congressman was. I said, \u2018I can\u2019t tell you that, it was pastoral privilege.\u2019 I said, \u2018I prayed for him\u2019 and he said, \u2018So, it was like a confession?\u2019 I said, \u2018Yeah, I can\u2019t tell you. I\u2019m not going to tell you, I can\u2019t tell you, it\u2019s impossible.'\u201d \u201cIf the Secret Service in Washington, D.C., don\u2019t know what\u2019s coming down, then why should somebody from Tampa?\u201d Howard-Browne added. \u201cThis is a senior member of Congress. If he actually knew anything, he would inform the Secret Service himself. It\u2019s not my problem.}}</ref> Howard-Browne praised God for giving America a 'Rambo'.<ref name=\"Right Wing Watch\">{{cite news |title=Rodney Howard-Browne Thanks God For Giving America \u2018A Rambo\u2019 In Trump|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-thanks-god-for-giving-america-a-rambo-in-trump/|date=18 May 2018| accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Howard-Browne wrote a Facebook post titled \u201cDonald Trump Is the New World Order\u2019s Worst Nightmare,\u201d where he detailed his choice to back Trump in the election as a check against a global conspiracy to destroy America.<ref name=\"Weaver\">{{cite news |last1=Weaver |first1=Hilary |title=Donald Trump\u2019s Oval Office Prayer Circle, Explained |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/07/donald-trump-oval-office-prayer-circle-explained |publisher=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=April 4, 2019 |date=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hurricane Irma===\nIn September 2017, Howard-Browne received media attention after referring to [[Hurricane Irma]]\u2014a [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|category 4]] storm that caused the death of 50 people in the U.S. and Caribbean and resulted in power outages affecting 5.5 million people in Florida\u2014as a \"nothingburger\". He further stated that \"prayer took the teeth out of the storm\".<ref name=\"Newsweek091217\">{{cite news |last1=Gaffey |first1=Conor |title=Hurricane Irma Was A Nothingburger, Says Pastor Who Prayed Over Trump At White House |url=https://www.newsweek.com/hurricane-irma-florida-trump-rodney-howard-browne-663594 |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |date=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Alleging human sacrifice===\nIn an October 2017 sermon at The River at Tampa Bay church, Howard-Browne alleged that \"They sacrifice children at the highest levels in Hollywood. They drink blood of young kids. This is a fact\", continuing, \"The human sacrifice and the cannibalism has been going on for years\" in Hollywood and Washington, D.C.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url = https://www.charismanews.com/56-video/67850-rodney-howard-browne-hollywood-execs-are-full-of-the-devil-drink-the-blood-of-young-kids\n | title = Rodney Howard Browne: Hollywood Execs Are 'Full of the Devil,' 'Drink the Blood of Young Kids'\n | last = Justice\n | first = Jessilyn\n | date = October 20, 2017 \n | website = Charisma News\n | publisher = Charisma Media\n | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = \"They sacrifice children at the highest levels in Hollywood. They drink blood of young kids. This is a fact. That's why the next thing to be exposed will be all the pedophilia that is going to come out of Hollywood and come out of Washington, D.C. The human sacrifice and the cannibalism has been going on for years\"}}</ref><ref>\n {{cite web\n  | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rodney-howard-browne-hollywood-devil-worship_us_59e96616e4b0f9d35bc9a27b\n  | title = Trump-Linked Pastor: Hollywood Is Full Of Satanists Who Drink Children\u2019s Blood\n  | last = Mazza\n  | first = Ed\n  | date = October 20, 2017\n  | website = Huffpost\n  | publisher = Oath Inc.\n  | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = }}\n</ref><ref name=\"CT102017\">{{cite news |last1=Macintyre |first1=James |title=Pastor who prayed over Donald Trump says Hollywood is full of devil worshippers who drink children's blood |url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/pastor-who-prayed-over-donald-trump-says-hollywood-is-full-of-devil-worshippers-who-drink-childrens-blood/116518.htm |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Christian Today]] |date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Arming of the River at Tampa Bay church===\nHoward-Browne drew attention for a social media post in November 2017, two days after the [[Sutherland Springs church shooting]], stating that his church was not a gun-free zone and that he and the church\u2019s pastors \u201care all heavily armed\u201d and would use \u201cdeadly force\u201d.<ref name=\"WaPo_112117\">{{cite news |last1=Eltagouri |first1=Marwa |title=This church has a warning for visitors: \u2018WE ARE HEAVILY ARMED \u2014 The Pastors\u2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2017/11/21/a-florida-church-has-a-warning-for-visitors-this-is-not-a-gun-free-zone-the-pastors/?noredirect=on |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Washington Post]] |date=November 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SJ\">{{cite news|last1=Denker|first1=Angela|title='We Are Heavily Armed. -The Pastors'|url=https://sojo.net/articles/we-are-heavily-armed-pastors|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Sojourners]]|date=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CBN112017\">{{cite news|last1=Aaron|first1=Charlene|title=After Deadly Church Shooting, Rodney Howard-Browne's Church Warns 'We Are Heavily Armed'|url=http://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2017/november/after-deadly-church-shooting-rodney-howard-brownes-church-warns-we-are-are-heavily-armed|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]]|date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Conspiracy theories on InfoWars===\nIn March 2018, Howard-Browne made an appearance on [[Alex Jones]]' [[InfoWars]] program during which he claimed: that a string of [[Austin bombings|bombings in Austin, Texas]] were being used by \"anarchist terrorists\" in an attempt to bring \"everything under control\"; that churches and religious groups were being censored in the U.S.; and that \"globalist gremlins\" were attempting to thwart Donald Trump.<ref name=\"RWW\">{{cite news|last1=Holt|first1=Jared|title=Rodney Howard-Browne Says Only \u2018Divine Intervention\u2019 Can Save America|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-says-only-divine-intervention-can-save-america/|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Right Wing Watch]]|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Christchurch Mosque shootings===\nShortly after the [[Christchurch mosque shootings]] in March 2019, Howard-Browne tweeted his opinion that it was a '[[false flag]]' operation: \"There is no doubt that what happened in New Zealand as horrific as it is, is a false flag that will be blamed on conservatives when it\u2019s all said and done!  Only a total nutjob lunatic, insane demonized freak goes into a building and kills people, it\u2019s unacceptable on every level!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rawstory.com/2019/03/megachurch-pastor-invited-trumps-white-house-declares-new-zealand-terror-attack-false-flag/|title=Megachurch pastor who was invited to Trump\u2019s White House declares New Zealand terror attack a \u2018false flag\u2019|first=Brad|last=Reed|website=www.rawstory.com}}</ref>\n\n===Iqaluit sermon===\nOn August 27, 2019, Howard-Browne delivered a sermon in the [[Canadian Arctic]] territory of [[Nunavut]] as part of a 300-city tour. He preached for over an hour at an [[Iqaluit]] church to a mostly [[Inuit]] audience of more than 100 people. The event featured a call for donations, including a video of Howard-Browne claiming \u201cGod loves a generous giver,\u201d which ''[[Nunatsiaq News]]'' criticized on the basis that poverty is widespread in the city and nearly half of Nunavut\u2019s population relies on social assistance amidst long-standing crises in food security and housing.<ref name=\"NunNews\"/> The news outlet also noted that he \u201clashed out\u201d at and \u201charangued\u201d audience members who tried to leave before the end of the sermon. Commenting after the event, [[Anglican bishop]] for the Arctic, [[David Parsons (bishop)|David Parsons]], described Howard-Browne as an [[extremist]].\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\n{{see also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nHoward-Browne kept his church open during the  [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]] and on March 15 told his congregants to continue shaking hands because they were \u201crevivalists, not pansies\u201d. He also claimed in his sermon that the pandemic was a \u201cphantom plague\u201d engineered by the Rockefeller Foundation to shut down churches and force people to receive a vaccine that would cause mass deaths, all as part of a population control scheme.<ref name=\"NW_031620\">{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Evan |title=Conservative pastor says his church 'will never close' because of coronavirus: 'we're raising up revivalists, not pansies' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/coronavirus-rodney-howard-browne-florida-pastor-pansies-1492460 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Indep_031620\">{{cite news |last1=Naughtie |first1=Andrew |title=Coronavirus: US conservatives spark backlash after socialising against official health advice |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/coronavirus-republican-kevin-stitt-restaurant-social-distancing-tweet-restaurant-a9404346.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[The Independent]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-coronavirus-pandemic-is-a-globalist-plot-to-kill-people-with-vaccines/|title=Rodney Howard-Browne: Coronavirus Pandemic Is a Globalist Plot to Kill People With Vaccines|first1=Kyle Mantyla &#124;|last1=March 16|first2=2020 10:24|last2=Am|website=Right Wing Watch|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref> Several weeks prior, Howard-Browne claimed in a video that he would cure Florida of coronavirus.<ref name=\"OW_022620\">{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Colin |title=Tampa pastor who claimed to cure Zika now says he will cure Florida of coronavirus |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/02/26/tampa-pastor-who-claimed-to-cure-zika-now-says-he-will-cure-florida-of-coronavirus |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[Orlando Weekly]] |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 29, 2020, Howard-Browne's congregation received a visit from the [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] about his violations of the county's safer-at-home order, which limited public gatherings to 10 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RightWingWatch/status/1244636146073812995|title=Right-wing pastor Rodney Howard-Browne has repeatedly stated that he will never cancel services at his The River church in Tampa. Now it looks like he received a visit from the local sheriff's office after holding services yesterday.pic.twitter.com/ABFYq4RtCg|first=|last=Right Wing Watch|date=Mar 30, 2020|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCN033020\"/> The next day, Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister announced that he had issued an arrest warrant to Howard-Browne for unlawful assembly and for violating rules regarding public health emergencies after Howard-Browne continued to hold large church services in defiance of the public order.<ref name=\"NYT033020\">{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |title=Florida Pastor Arrested After Defying Virus Orders |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/us/coronavirus-pastor-arrested-tampa-florida.html |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TBT033020\">{{cite news |last1=Marrero |first1=Tony |title=Pastor of Tampa church that held two large Sunday services arrested, jailed |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/health/2020/03/30/tampa-church-holds-packed-service-draws-warning-from-sheriffs-office/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/HCSOSheriff/videos/230907918296583/|title=Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office on Facebook Watch|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020|via=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref>Mantyla, Kyle (March 30, 2020). \"[https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/arrest-warrant-issued-for-rodney-howard-browne-for-hosting-church-services-amid-the-coronavirus-outbreak/ Arrest Warrant Issued for Rodney Howard-Browne for Hosting Church Services Amid Coronavirus Pandemic]\". [[Right Wing Watch]].</ref> Chronister said he had no choice but to take action against Howard-Browne, stating \"His reckless disregard for human life put hundreds of people from his congregation at risk and thousands of residents who may interact with them this week.\"<ref name=\"NBCN033020\">{{cite news |last1=Li |first1=David K |title=Florida pastor arrested after holding church services despite coronavirus orders |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/florida-pastor-arrested-after-holding-church-services-despite-coronavirus-orders-n1172276 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 30, 2020, Howard-Browne was arrested and jailed for unlawful assembly and for violating health and safety rules, with each charge carrying a maximum penalty of 60 days in jail and a $500 fine.<ref name=\"TBT033020\"/><ref name=\"NYT033020\"/> He was released from jail after posting a $500 bond.<ref>Sommer, Will and Connor, Tracy (March 30, 2020). \"[https://www.thedailybeast.com/hillsborough-sheriff-to-arrest-rodney-howard-browne-megachurch-pastor-who-flouted-virus-rules|Rodney Howard-Browne, Megachurch Pastor Who Flouted Virus Rules, Arrested.]\" [[The Daily Beast]].</ref>\n\nOn April 1, Howard-Browne said that he would not open his church the following weekend over fear of his congregation\u2019s safety and to protect them from \u201cgovernment tyranny.\"<ref name=\"OW040320\">{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Colin |title=Orlando lawyer for pastor who held services during coronavirus outbreak says church lost its insurance |url=https://m.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/04/03/orlando-lawyer-for-pastor-who-held-services-during-coronavirus-outbreak-says-church-lost-its-insurance |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |publisher=[[Orlando Weekly]] |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> However, his lawyer, [[Mathew Staver]] of the law firm [[Liberty Counsel]], said that Howard-Browne\u2019s arrest earlier in the week had led to the pastor\u2019s insurance policy being cancelled.<ref name=\"OW040320\"/><ref name=\"NBCN041020\">{{cite news |last1=Siemaszko |first1=Corky |title=Florida megachurch pastor caves after defying coronavirus rules |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/florida-megachurch-pastor-caves-after-defying-coronavirus-rules-n1181491 |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Howard-Browne also claimed and that he had received death threats. The pastor held open the possibility that the church would be open for [[Easter]] services but then announced on April 9 that it would instead be closed.<ref name=\"NBCN041020\"/>\n\n== Publications ==\n*''The Killing of Uncle Sam: The Demise of the United States of America'' by Rodney Howard-Browne and [[Paul L. Williams (author)|Paul L. Williams]]\n*''How to Increase and Release the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''Manifesting the Holy Ghost to You, in You, and Through You'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''How to Increase and Release the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''School of the Spirit'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''The Touch of God: A Practical Handbook on the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''Seeing Jesus as He Really Is'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.revival.com Revival Ministries International website]\n*[https://www.riverschoolofgovernment.com River School of Government]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howard-Browne, Rodney}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Christian revivalists]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:Faith healers]]\n[[Category:People from the Eastern Cape]]\n[[Category:South African Charismatics]]\n[[Category:South African clergy]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian clergy]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christian clergy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African preacher}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Rodney Howard-Browne\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = Rodney Morgan Howard Browne<ref name=\"TORONTOBLESSING\">{{Cite web|url=http://jbeard.users.rapidnet.com/bdm/Psychology/holylaugh.htm|title=Holy Laughter - Rodney Howard-Browne and the Toronto Blessing|website=jbeard.users.rapidnet.com|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1961|6|12}}<ref name=\"TORONTOBLESSING\"></ref>\n|birth_place   = [[Port Elizabeth]], South Africa\n|residence=[[Tampa, Florida]], U.S.\n|nationality   = South African\n|spouse        = Adonica Howard-Browne (nee Weyers)\n|website       = [http://www.revival.com Revival Ministries International]\n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Rodney (Morgan) Howard-Browne''' (born June 12, 1961)<ref name=\"HCDC\">{{cite web |title=Hernando County Inmate Booking Information: Rodney Howard Browne |url=https://www.hernandosheriff.org/jail/Applications/JailSearch/JailSearchDetails.aspx?BookNo=HCSO20JBN002084 |website=Hernando County Detention Center |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> is a South African-born American Christian [[Evangelism|evangelist]] and pastor of The River church in Tampa Bay.  He has resided in [[Tampa]], [[Florida]] since the mid-1990s. The River is considered both [[Pentecostal]] and [[Charismatic]] with [[revival meetings]], led by Howard-Browne, known for those in the audience breaking into \"[[holy laughter]]\".<ref name=\"TBT\"/><ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=ravitz/><ref name=\"VOA\"/>  Howard-Browne is the head of Revival Ministries International, a group he and his wife founded in 1997.\n\n==Biography==\nHoward-Browne and his three brothers (Mervyn, Bazil, and Gil) were raised in a [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] family in the cities of [[Port Elizabeth]] and [[East London, Eastern Cape|East London]], South Africa. His father, Frank Mervyn Derric Howard-Browne (1924\u20132005),<ref name=\"TBT090205\">{{cite news |title=Frank Howard-Browne Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tampabaytimes/obituary.aspx?n=frank-howard-browne&pid=15005170 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=September 2, 2005}}</ref> was a cleric.  Howard-Browne became a Christian at age five.<ref name=\"M&G\"/> In 1981, he met and married his wife Adonica (n\u00e9e Weyers).<ref name=ravitz>Ravitz, Jessica. [https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=5294497&itype=NGPSID \"Up for Godly giddiness: Pastor spreads the joy of salvation 'anywhere the Lord opens a door.'\"] The Salt Lake Tribune, March 22, 2007</ref> In the 1980s, he volunteered to work for [[Youth for Christ]] before doing a teaching stint with Rhema Bible School in [[Johannesburg]].\n\nIn December 1989, the family emigrated from South Africa to the United States,<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week251/profile.html \"Profile: Evangelist Rodney Howard-Browne.\"] Religion and Ethics NewsWeekly, PBS, August 20, 1999</ref><ref name=\"M&G\">{{cite news |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-03-16-gods-bartender-in-good-spirits|last1=Philp |first1=Rowan Philp |title=God's bartender in good spirits |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Mail & Guardian]] |date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> settling in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], and in 1991, he began holding revival meetings.<ref name=\"TBT090205\"/><ref name=\"Time062401\"/><ref name=\"RMI1\">{{cite web |title=History of Campmeetings |url=https://www.revival.com/index.html |website=Revival Ministries International |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |quote=Through the summer of 1991, we held revival meetings in Louisville, Kentucky, and all over the surrounding\u2026}}</ref> The Rodney Howard-Browne Evangelistic Association was incorporated in November 1993<ref name=\"FDS\">{{cite web |title=Rodney Howard Brown Evangelistic Association, Inc.: Annual Report 1994 |url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/ConvertTiffToPDF?storagePath=COR%5C0107%5C0105%5CAR000589.tif&documentNumber=F93000005142 |publisher=Florida Department of State, Division of Corporations |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref> and the family moved to the [[Tampa Bay, Florida]] area in 1994. Rodney's eldest brother Gil<ref name=\"TBT090205\"/> went on to operate Times of Refreshing Ministries, an online evangelical ministry.<ref name=\"TORM\">{{cite web |title=Times of Refreshing Ministries:The Internet Ministry of Evangelists Gil & Loraine Howard-Browne \u2013 About Us |url=http://revivaltimes.com/about.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref>. Likewise, his youngest brother Bazil established an eponymous evangelical ministry on 1 January 1994 with the professed aim of people achieving financial freedom through the special anointing of God <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bhbem.wordpress.com/2009/05/26/what-you-need-to-know-about-bazil-howard-browne/|title=What you need to know about Bazil Howard-Browne|date=May 26, 2009|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>. Prior to this he had worked alongside his brother Rodney for a year.\n\nIn 1996, Howard-Browne founded a church he named \"The River\" at Tampa Bay Church in [[Tampa, Florida]], serving as its pastor ever since.<ref name=\"TBT011005\">{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=Kevin |title=Church's Hummer prize too worldly? |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/01/10/Hillsborough/Church_s_Hummer_prize.shtml |accessdate=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=January 10, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326000430/http://www.sptimes.com/2005/01/10/Hillsborough/Church_s_Hummer_prize.shtml |archivedate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> Howard-Browne and his wife also founded Revival Ministries International in 1997, as well as River Bible Institute and River School of Worship.<ref>Howard-Browne, Rodney [https://www.revival.com/about \"About us\"] Revival.com</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne\u2019s services are characterized by [[faith healing|laying on of hands]] with worshipers giggling in apparent [[spiritual drunkenness]], [[speaking in tongues]], emitting animal noises, breaking into uncontrollable [[holy laughter]], shaking, dancing in the aisles, or falling to the ground.<ref name=\"TBT\"/><ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=ravitz/><ref name=\"VOA\">{{cite news |last1=Socolovsky |first1=Jerome |title=African-born Pastor Brings \u2018Holy Laughter\u2019 Revival to Washington |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/african-born-pastor-brings-holy-laughter-revival-to-washington/1954365.html|accessdate=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Voice of America]] |date=July 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"NunNews\">{{cite news |last1=Rohner |first1=Thomas |title=Conspiracy-theorizing megachurch preacher visits Nunavut|url=https://nunatsiaq.com/stories/article/conspiracy-theorizing-megachurch-preacher-visits-nunavut/ |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Nunatsiaq News]] |date=September 5, 2019 |quote=Howard-Browne also spoke in tongues, which he claimed was once understood in the obscure native dialect of a Papua New Guinea pastor}}</ref> He refers to himself as \"God's bartender\" and the \"holy ghost bartender\".<ref name=\"carnes\">Carnes, Tony. [http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/1999/august9/9t913a.html \"Howard-Browne Takes New York.\"] Christianity Today, August 9, 1999</ref><ref name=\"TBT\">{{cite news|url=http://tampabayonline.net/reports/minister/homealt.htm|title=The Holy Ghost Bartender|last=Bearden|first=Michelle|date=1999-06-28|newspaper=[[The Tampa Tribune]]|accessdate=2019-02-23|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707031815/http://tampabayonline.net/reports/minister/homealt.htm|archivedate=2012-07-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne is credited with introducing holy laughter to [[Carpenter's Home Church]] in [[Lakeland, Florida]] during a series of revival services with Karl Strader in 1993. The holy laughter revivals later spread to nearby churches in Melbourne, Titusville, Stuart and Vero Beach, Florida.<ref name=\"OS090196\">{{cite news |last1=Pinsky |first1=Mark I |title=When Holy Laughter Starts, Some Find It Hard To Stop |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1996-09-01-9608310934-story.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 1, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Ledger051808\">{{cite news |last1=McMullen |first1=Cary |title=Florida Outpouring: Internet Draws Thousands to Lakeland Revival |url= https://www.theledger.com/article/LK/20080518/News/608117817/LL/ |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[The Ledger]] |date=May 18, 2008}}</ref> Howard-Browne is credited with bringing holy laughter to the charismatic Toronto Airport Vineyard Church (soon after expelled by its parent [[Association of Vineyard Churches|Vineyard Church]]) at a 1994 revival in [[Toronto, Canada]] with evangelist Randy Clark, known as the \u201c[[Toronto Blessing]],\" and then a year later, to [[Assemblies of God]] (AOG) Brownsville Church in [[Pensacola, Florida]] with evangelist [[Steve Hill (evangelist)|Steve Hill]].  The event became known in Christian circles as the [[Brownsville Revival]].<ref name=\"OS090196\"/><ref name=\"Ledger051808\"/><ref name=\"Time062401\">{{cite news |last1=Ostling |first1=Richard N |title=Laughing for the Lord |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,164903,00.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Time Magazine]] |date=June 24, 2001}}</ref> Howard-Browne also ministered under pastor Mike Rose at the Juneau Christian Center (formerly known as the Bethel Assembly of God) in [[Juneau, Alaska]], an AOG church that [[Sarah Palin]] later attended after becoming governor of Alaska.<ref name=\"HuffPo101208\">{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Bruce |title=Palin and the Holy Laughter Anointing |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/palin-and-the-holy-laught_b_125582 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Huffington Post]] |date=October 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR090508\">{{cite news |last1=Bradley Hagerty |first1=Barbara |title=Examining Palin's Pentecostal Background |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=94332540 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=September 5, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Hapers083008\">{{cite news |last1=Silverstein |first1=Ken |title=Palin and Her Pastors: \"Those that die without Christ have a horrible, horrible surprise\" |url=https://harpers.org/blog/2008/08/palin-and-her-pastors-those-that-die-without-christ-have-a-horrible-horrible-surprise/ |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Harper's Magazine]] |date=August 30, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek102708\">{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Lisa |title=What Are Sarah Palin\u2019s Religious Beliefs? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/what-are-sarah-palins-religious-beliefs-91785 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |date=October 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne first came to national prominence in the US in 1999 when his Revival Ministries organization rented [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City for six weeks. The event, called Good News New York, was described as \u201can effort to achieve a Billy Graham-style faith uprising\u201d, but was \u201cderided in local media as a giant flop\u201d. It was estimated to cost up to $10 million but only 3,000 people were counted in attendance at the 19,000-seat arena.<ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=\"TBT\"/> Investigative journalists in his home town of Tampa reported at the time that since arriving from South Africa almost penniless in December 1989, his sudden wealth included a boat, a [[Harley Davidson]] motorcycle, a home in one of Tampa\u2019s exclusive gated communities and access to a private jet; however, they were unable to find evidence of financial wrongdoing.<ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"TBT\"/>\n\nHoward-Browne\u2019s daughter Kelly died due to cystic fibrosis on Christmas Day, 25 December 2002, at the age of 18. He then vowed that \u201csince the devil has taken their daughter with this dreaded disease, he would pay with one million souls over the next ten years\u201d.<ref name=\"Kambulow\"/><ref name=\"TBT122802\">{{cite news |title=Kelly Howard-Browne Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tampabaytimes/obituary.aspx?n=kelly-howard-browne&pid=680575 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=December 28, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, it was reported that Howard-Browne\u2019s River Church had hosted political meetings for the Florida chapter of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] during the preceding two years, including a rally for then presidential candidate [[Newt Gingrich]], at which Howard-Browne called for a national \"rising\" of Christian Americans \"that will not sit idly by and allow the killing of unborn babies and allow Islam to take over this country\". At the same event, he described [[Mormonism]] as a \"cult\" that, in the 19th century, \"had death squads that would go around killing everybody that was not a Mormon\". He later took the remark back, saying Mormons were \"honourable people\".<ref name=\"M&G\"/>\n\nHoward-Browne published ''The Killing of Uncle Sam: The Demise of the United States of America'', which was scheduled to be released in May 2018, and announced that proceeds from sales of the book would go to the River School of Government, a degree granting program, operated by Howard-Browne and his wife under the auspices of Revival Ministries, that funds training for people seeking to run for political office.<ref name=\"DFP\">{{cite news |last1=McGregor |first1=Grady |title=Controversial pastor visits Dickinson: Rival pastor from Montana dragged from church after protesting |url=https://www.thedickinsonpress.com/news/4360976-controversial-pastor-visits-dickinson-rival-pastor-montana-dragged-church-after |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Dickinson Press]] |date=November 17, 2017}}</ref>  \n\nHoward-Browne's evangelical movement has been rejected as cult-like by many mainstream Christian organisations, and it has been described as \"a combination of brimstone and fire about God\u2019s power, sprinkled with hipster references and a conviction that church\u2014like Disneyland\u2014should be 'the happiest place on earth'.\"<ref name=\"M&G\"/> The Christian Research Institute labelled his operation a \u201ccult\u201d and called the him \"a good stage hypnotist\" who has made millions from vulnerable believers.<ref name=\"M&G\"/> According to ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]'', critics have described him as \"a manipulator leading followers into a cult; a circus ring leader making a good living.\"<ref name=\"TBT\"/>\n\n==Statements and controversies==\n===Diploma mill doctorate===\nHoward-Browne claimed to have earned a \"doctorate of ministry degree\" in 1992  from \"The School of Bible Theology\", a [[non-accredited]] Pentecostal correspondence school in San Jacinto, California that has been described as a \"[[diploma mill]]\".<ref name=TBT/><ref name=\"AI1\">{{cite news|last1=Kowalski|first1=David|title=\"Name it and Frame it\" \u2014 Phony Doctorates in the Church|url=http://www.apologeticsindex.org/2794-name-it-and-frame-it-phony-doctorates-in-the-church|accessdate=May 3, 2018|publisher=Apologetics Index|date=2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dSur1KLjWIUC&source=gbs_navlinks_s|last1=Stokes |first1=Jerry |title=Joseph Smith and Word of Faith Movement |page=21 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Kambulow\">{{cite book |last1=Kambulow |first1=Walter |title=The Best of the Kambulows |date=June 1, 2003 |page=879 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/THE_BEST_OF_THE_KAMBULOW.html?id=YS3cAgAAQBAJ |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Multi-level marketing: Monavie and Jeunesse===\nHoward-Browne and his wife Adonica were top-ranking (\u201cBlack Diamond executive level\u201d) distributors for [[Monavie]], a [[multi-level marketing]] company that sold [[acai berry]] juice-based beverages until folding in 2014 subsequent to a $182 million loan default and allegations of [[pyramid scheme|pyramid scheming]], fraudulent advertising, and [[patent infringement]].<ref>{{cite web |title=MV Three Sixty Five Magazine |url=https://www.team-legacy.info/PDF/MV365_Magazine.pdf |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |pages=86}}</ref><ref name=\"YT\">{{cite news|title=Rodney and Adonica Howard-Browne MonaVie Black Diamond|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdXhteTaPpE|accessdate=May 2, 2018|agency=YouTube|publisher=[[Monavie|Monavie Corporate]]|date=March 18, 2009}}</ref><ref name=imagenetixdocket>{{cite web| title = Imagenetix, Inc. vs. Monavie LLC et al. | publisher = [[United States District Court]] for the Southern District of California | date = May 2, 2018 | url = https://ia800205.us.archive.org/20/items/gov.uscourts.casd.269686/gov.uscourts.casd.269686.1.0.pdf| accessdate = 2008-09-20}}</ref> As of 2016, Howard-Browne also served as a \"North America Emerald Director\" for the multi-level marketing company Jeunesse.<ref name=\"Jeunesse\">{{cite web |title=Legacy Powered by Jeunesse |url=https://www.team-legacy.com/PDF/OurTeam-OurProducts.pdf |publisher=Jeunesse Global Holdings, LLC |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |page=41 |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Allegation of plot to attack Donald Trump ===\nIn July 2017, Howard-Browne was one of 17 evangelical pastors who visited the [[White House]] to pray for and [[laying on of hands|lay hands]] on President [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"KCS\">{{cite news|last1=Gutierrez|first1=Lisa|title=\u2018Great spiritual awakening\u2019: Pastors lay hands on Donald Trump in the Oval Office|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/nation-world/article160904779.html|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=July 12, 2017}}</ref> In a video several days later, Howard-Browne stated that \u201cthere is a planned attack on our president and that\u2019s all I can tell you about right now; I know what I\u2019m talking about, I\u2019ve spoken to high-ranking people in the government\".<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-prayed-over-trump-in-order-to-avert-a-planned-attack-on-our-president/\n | title = Rodney Howard-Browne Prayed Over Trump In Order To Avert \u2018A Planned Attack On Our President\u2019 \n | last = Mantyla\n | first = Kyle\n | date = July 17, 2017\n | website = Right Wing Watch\n | publisher = People for the American Way\n | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = There is a planned attack on our president,\" he said, \u201cand that\u2019s all I can tell you about right now; I know what I\u2019m talking about, I\u2019ve spoken to high-ranking people in the government and this is being planned by people that hate God, hate America, hate our president and we have to stop this, in Jesus name.\u201d}}</ref> Howard-Browne later said that the Secret Service met with him to discover which congressman told him about the plot but he refused to say, citing pastoral privilege.<ref>\n {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/its-not-my-problem-rodney-howard-browne-refused-to-provide-the-secret-service-with-details-of-a-plot-again-trump/\n  | title = Pastor Who Claimed His Prayers Averted Anti-Trump Attack Refuses To Provide Details To Secret Service Because It\u2019s \u2018Not My Problem\u2019\n  | last = Mantyla\n  | first = Kyle\n  | date = July 31, 2017\n  | website = Right Wing Watch\n  | publisher = Right Wing Watch\n  | access-date = 21 December 2017\n | quote = Somebody reported me to the Secret Service, so they came over\u201d he claimed. \u201cThree guys, we sat and talked; very nice people and they wanted to know who the congressman was. I said, \u2018I can\u2019t tell you that, it was pastoral privilege.\u2019 I said, \u2018I prayed for him\u2019 and he said, \u2018So, it was like a confession?\u2019 I said, \u2018Yeah, I can\u2019t tell you. I\u2019m not going to tell you, I can\u2019t tell you, it\u2019s impossible.'\u201d \u201cIf the Secret Service in Washington, D.C., don\u2019t know what\u2019s coming down, then why should somebody from Tampa?\u201d Howard-Browne added. \u201cThis is a senior member of Congress. If he actually knew anything, he would inform the Secret Service himself. It\u2019s not my problem.}}</ref> Howard-Browne praised God for giving America a 'Rambo'.<ref name=\"Right Wing Watch\">{{cite news |title=Rodney Howard-Browne Thanks God For Giving America \u2018A Rambo\u2019 In Trump|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-thanks-god-for-giving-america-a-rambo-in-trump/|date=18 May 2018| accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Howard-Browne wrote a Facebook post titled \u201cDonald Trump Is the New World Order\u2019s Worst Nightmare,\u201d where he detailed his choice to back Trump in the election as a check against a global conspiracy to destroy America.<ref name=\"Weaver\">{{cite news |last1=Weaver |first1=Hilary |title=Donald Trump\u2019s Oval Office Prayer Circle, Explained |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/07/donald-trump-oval-office-prayer-circle-explained |publisher=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=April 4, 2019 |date=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hurricane Irma===\nIn September 2017, Howard-Browne received media attention after referring to [[Hurricane Irma]]\u2014a [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|category 4]] storm that caused the death of 50 people in the U.S. and Caribbean and resulted in power outages affecting 5.5 million people in Florida\u2014as a \"nothingburger\". He further stated that \"prayer took the teeth out of the storm\".<ref name=\"Newsweek091217\">{{cite news |last1=Gaffey |first1=Conor |title=Hurricane Irma Was A Nothingburger, Says Pastor Who Prayed Over Trump At White House |url=https://www.newsweek.com/hurricane-irma-florida-trump-rodney-howard-browne-663594 |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |date=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Alleging human sacrifice===\nIn an October 2017 sermon at The River at Tampa Bay church, Howard-Browne alleged that \"They sacrifice children at the highest levels in Hollywood. They drink blood of young kids. This is a fact\", continuing, \"The human sacrifice and the cannibalism has been going on for years\" in Hollywood and Washington, D.C.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url = https://www.charismanews.com/56-video/67850-rodney-howard-browne-hollywood-execs-are-full-of-the-devil-drink-the-blood-of-young-kids\n | title = Rodney Howard Browne: Hollywood Execs Are 'Full of the Devil,' 'Drink the Blood of Young Kids'\n | last = Justice\n | first = Jessilyn\n | date = October 20, 2017 \n | website = Charisma News\n | publisher = Charisma Media\n | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = \"They sacrifice children at the highest levels in Hollywood. They drink blood of young kids. This is a fact. That's why the next thing to be exposed will be all the pedophilia that is going to come out of Hollywood and come out of Washington, D.C. The human sacrifice and the cannibalism has been going on for years\"}}</ref><ref>\n {{cite web\n  | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rodney-howard-browne-hollywood-devil-worship_us_59e96616e4b0f9d35bc9a27b\n  | title = Trump-Linked Pastor: Hollywood Is Full Of Satanists Who Drink Children\u2019s Blood\n  | last = Mazza\n  | first = Ed\n  | date = October 20, 2017\n  | website = Huffpost\n  | publisher = Oath Inc.\n  | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = }}\n</ref><ref name=\"CT102017\">{{cite news |last1=Macintyre |first1=James |title=Pastor who prayed over Donald Trump says Hollywood is full of devil worshippers who drink children's blood |url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/pastor-who-prayed-over-donald-trump-says-hollywood-is-full-of-devil-worshippers-who-drink-childrens-blood/116518.htm |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Christian Today]] |date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Arming of the River at Tampa Bay church===\nHoward-Browne drew attention for a social media post in November 2017, two days after the [[Sutherland Springs church shooting]], stating that his church was not a gun-free zone and that he and the church\u2019s pastors \u201care all heavily armed\u201d and would use \u201cdeadly force\u201d.<ref name=\"WaPo_112117\">{{cite news |last1=Eltagouri |first1=Marwa |title=This church has a warning for visitors: \u2018WE ARE HEAVILY ARMED \u2014 The Pastors\u2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2017/11/21/a-florida-church-has-a-warning-for-visitors-this-is-not-a-gun-free-zone-the-pastors/?noredirect=on |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Washington Post]] |date=November 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SJ\">{{cite news|last1=Denker|first1=Angela|title='We Are Heavily Armed. -The Pastors'|url=https://sojo.net/articles/we-are-heavily-armed-pastors|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Sojourners]]|date=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CBN112017\">{{cite news|last1=Aaron|first1=Charlene|title=After Deadly Church Shooting, Rodney Howard-Browne's Church Warns 'We Are Heavily Armed'|url=http://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2017/november/after-deadly-church-shooting-rodney-howard-brownes-church-warns-we-are-are-heavily-armed|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]]|date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Conspiracy theories on InfoWars===\nIn March 2018, Howard-Browne made an appearance on [[Alex Jones]]' [[InfoWars]] program during which he claimed: that a string of [[Austin bombings|bombings in Austin, Texas]] were being used by \"anarchist terrorists\" in an attempt to bring \"everything under control\"; that churches and religious groups were being censored in the U.S.; and that \"globalist gremlins\" were attempting to thwart Donald Trump.<ref name=\"RWW\">{{cite news|last1=Holt|first1=Jared|title=Rodney Howard-Browne Says Only \u2018Divine Intervention\u2019 Can Save America|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-says-only-divine-intervention-can-save-america/|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Right Wing Watch]]|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Christchurch Mosque shootings===\nShortly after the [[Christchurch mosque shootings]] in March 2019, Howard-Browne tweeted his opinion that it was a '[[false flag]]' operation: \"There is no doubt that what happened in New Zealand as horrific as it is, is a false flag that will be blamed on conservatives when it\u2019s all said and done!  Only a total nutjob lunatic, insane demonized freak goes into a building and kills people, it\u2019s unacceptable on every level!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rawstory.com/2019/03/megachurch-pastor-invited-trumps-white-house-declares-new-zealand-terror-attack-false-flag/|title=Megachurch pastor who was invited to Trump\u2019s White House declares New Zealand terror attack a \u2018false flag\u2019|first=Brad|last=Reed|website=www.rawstory.com}}</ref>\n\n===Iqaluit sermon===\nOn August 27, 2019, Howard-Browne delivered a sermon in the [[Canadian Arctic]] territory of [[Nunavut]] as part of a 300-city tour. He preached for over an hour at an [[Iqaluit]] church to a mostly [[Inuit]] audience of more than 100 people. The event featured a call for donations, including a video of Howard-Browne claiming \u201cGod loves a generous giver,\u201d which ''[[Nunatsiaq News]]'' criticized on the basis that poverty is widespread in the city and nearly half of Nunavut\u2019s population relies on social assistance amidst long-standing crises in food security and housing.<ref name=\"NunNews\"/> The news outlet also noted that he \u201clashed out\u201d at and \u201charangued\u201d audience members who tried to leave before the end of the sermon. Commenting after the event, [[Anglican bishop]] for the Arctic, [[David Parsons (bishop)|David Parsons]], described Howard-Browne as an [[extremist]].\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\n{{see also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nHoward-Browne kept his church open during the  [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]] and on March 15 told his congregants to continue shaking hands because they were \u201crevivalists, not pansies\u201d. He also claimed in his sermon that the pandemic was a \u201cphantom plague\u201d engineered by the Rockefeller Foundation to shut down churches and force people to receive a vaccine that would cause mass deaths, all as part of a population control scheme.<ref name=\"NW_031620\">{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Evan |title=Conservative pastor says his church 'will never close' because of coronavirus: 'we're raising up revivalists, not pansies' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/coronavirus-rodney-howard-browne-florida-pastor-pansies-1492460 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Indep_031620\">{{cite news |last1=Naughtie |first1=Andrew |title=Coronavirus: US conservatives spark backlash after socialising against official health advice |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/coronavirus-republican-kevin-stitt-restaurant-social-distancing-tweet-restaurant-a9404346.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[The Independent]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-coronavirus-pandemic-is-a-globalist-plot-to-kill-people-with-vaccines/|title=Rodney Howard-Browne: Coronavirus Pandemic Is a Globalist Plot to Kill People With Vaccines|first1=Kyle Mantyla &#124;|last1=March 16|first2=2020 10:24|last2=Am|website=Right Wing Watch|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref> Several weeks prior, Howard-Browne claimed in a video that he would cure Florida of coronavirus.<ref name=\"OW_022620\">{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Colin |title=Tampa pastor who claimed to cure Zika now says he will cure Florida of coronavirus |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/02/26/tampa-pastor-who-claimed-to-cure-zika-now-says-he-will-cure-florida-of-coronavirus |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[Orlando Weekly]] |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 29, 2020, Howard-Browne's congregation received a visit from the [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] about his violations of the county's safer-at-home order, which limited public gatherings to 10 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RightWingWatch/status/1244636146073812995|title=Right-wing pastor Rodney Howard-Browne has repeatedly stated that he will never cancel services at his The River church in Tampa. Now it looks like he received a visit from the local sheriff's office after holding services yesterday.pic.twitter.com/ABFYq4RtCg|first=|last=Right Wing Watch|date=Mar 30, 2020|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCN033020\"/> The next day, Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister announced that he had issued an arrest warrant to Howard-Browne for unlawful assembly and for violating rules regarding public health emergencies after Howard-Browne continued to hold large church services in defiance of the public order.<ref name=\"NYT033020\">{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |title=Florida Pastor Arrested After Defying Virus Orders |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/us/coronavirus-pastor-arrested-tampa-florida.html |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TBT033020\">{{cite news |last1=Marrero |first1=Tony |title=Pastor of Tampa church that held two large Sunday services arrested, jailed |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/health/2020/03/30/tampa-church-holds-packed-service-draws-warning-from-sheriffs-office/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/HCSOSheriff/videos/230907918296583/|title=Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office on Facebook Watch|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020|via=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref>Mantyla, Kyle (March 30, 2020). \"[https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/arrest-warrant-issued-for-rodney-howard-browne-for-hosting-church-services-amid-the-coronavirus-outbreak/ Arrest Warrant Issued for Rodney Howard-Browne for Hosting Church Services Amid Coronavirus Pandemic]\". [[Right Wing Watch]].</ref> Chronister said he had no choice but to take action against Howard-Browne, stating \"His reckless disregard for human life put hundreds of people from his congregation at risk and thousands of residents who may interact with them this week.\"<ref name=\"NBCN033020\">{{cite news |last1=Li |first1=David K |title=Florida pastor arrested after holding church services despite coronavirus orders |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/florida-pastor-arrested-after-holding-church-services-despite-coronavirus-orders-n1172276 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 30, 2020, Howard-Browne was arrested and jailed for unlawful assembly and for violating health and safety rules, with each charge carrying a maximum penalty of 60 days in jail and a $500 fine.<ref name=\"TBT033020\"/><ref name=\"NYT033020\"/> He was released from jail after posting a $500 bond.<ref>Sommer, Will and Connor, Tracy (March 30, 2020). \"[https://www.thedailybeast.com/hillsborough-sheriff-to-arrest-rodney-howard-browne-megachurch-pastor-who-flouted-virus-rules|Rodney Howard-Browne, Megachurch Pastor Who Flouted Virus Rules, Arrested.]\" [[The Daily Beast]].</ref>\n\nOn April 1, Howard-Browne said that he would not open his church the following weekend over fear of his congregation\u2019s safety and to protect them from \u201cgovernment tyranny.\"<ref name=\"OW040320\">{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Colin |title=Orlando lawyer for pastor who held services during coronavirus outbreak says church lost its insurance |url=https://m.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/04/03/orlando-lawyer-for-pastor-who-held-services-during-coronavirus-outbreak-says-church-lost-its-insurance |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |publisher=[[Orlando Weekly]] |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> However, his lawyer, [[Mathew Staver]] of the law firm [[Liberty Counsel]], said that Howard-Browne\u2019s arrest earlier in the week had led to the pastor\u2019s insurance policy being cancelled.<ref name=\"OW040320\"/><ref name=\"NBCN041020\">{{cite news |last1=Siemaszko |first1=Corky |title=Florida megachurch pastor caves after defying coronavirus rules |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/florida-megachurch-pastor-caves-after-defying-coronavirus-rules-n1181491 |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Howard-Browne also claimed and that he had received death threats. The pastor held open the possibility that the church would be open for [[Easter]] services but then announced on April 9 that it would instead be closed.<ref name=\"NBCN041020\"/>\n\n== Publications ==\n*''The Killing of Uncle Sam: The Demise of the United States of America'' by Rodney Howard-Browne and [[Paul L. Williams (author)|Paul L. Williams]]\n*''How to Increase and Release the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''Manifesting the Holy Ghost to You, in You, and Through You'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''How to Increase and Release the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''School of the Spirit'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''The Touch of God: A Practical Handbook on the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''Seeing Jesus as He Really Is'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.revival.com Revival Ministries International website]\n*[https://www.riverschoolofgovernment.com River School of Government]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howard-Browne, Rodney}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Christian revivalists]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:Faith healers]]\n[[Category:People from the Eastern Cape]]\n[[Category:South African Charismatics]]\n[[Category:South African clergy]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian clergy]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christian clergy]]\n", "name_user": "Rhode Island Red", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:a remark cannot be \"taken back\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodney_Howard-Browne"}
{"title_page": "Juro Que", "text_new": "{{short description|2020 single by Rosal\u00eda}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name          = Juro Que\n| type          = single\n| cover         = RosaliaJuroQue.png \n| artist        = [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]]\n| language      = Spanish\n| English_title = \"I Swear That\"\n| album         =\n| released      = {{Start date|2020|1|23|df=y}}\n| recorded      = <!-- Please source recording dates/years -->\n| studio        =\n| format        = {{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n| genre         = <!-- Please source genres -->\n| length        = {{duration|m=2|s=50}}\n| label         = {{hlist|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|[[Sony Music|Sony]]}}\n| writer        = {{hlist|[[El Guincho|Pablo D\u00edaz-Reixa]]|Kaydy Cain|[[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda Vila]]}}\n| producer      = El Guincho\n| chronology    = [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]]\n| prev_title    = [[Highest in the Room#Rosal\u00eda and Lil Baby remix|Highest in the Room (Remix)]]\n| prev_year     = 2020\n| next_title    = [[Dolerme]]\n| next_year     = 2020\n| misc          = {{External music video|{{YouTube|mtym36PG6R8|\"Juro Que\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Juro Que'''\"  ({{trans|\"I Swear That\"}}) is a song performed by Spanish singer and songwriter [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda]]. It was released through [[Sony Music|Sony]] and [[Columbia Records]] on 23 January 2020 as a single from her upcoming third studio album, which is set to be released this year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://los40.com/los40/2019/10/01/musica/1569917125_264720.html|title=Rosal\u00eda desvela cuando saldr\u00e1 su pr\u00f3ximo disco|last=Rodrigo|first=Javi|website=[[Los 40]]|language=es|date=1 October 2019|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> The song talks about the imprisonment of a lover. \"Juro Que\" brings Rosal\u00eda back to her [[Flamenco fusi\u00f3n|flamenco fusion]] days thanks to the presence of a [[Flamenco guitar|Spanish guitar]], aggressive guitar chords and minimal production. It was performed in a shortened version at the [[62nd Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/rosalia-brings-flamenco-flavor-to-2020-grammy-awards-performance-140165|title=Rosal\u00eda Brings Flamenco Flavor to 2020 GRAMMY Awards Performance|website=Entertainment Tonight|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-01}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nOn 22 January 2020, Rosal\u00eda posted a picture with Spanish ''[[Elite (TV series)|\u00c9lite]]'' star Omar Ayuso on her respective social media profiles with the caption \"Juro que\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lavanguardia.com/muyfan/20200122/473065741721/rosalia-omar-ayuso-elite.html|title=\u00bfQu\u00e9 hacen la cantante Rosal\u00eda y Omar Ayuso de \u2018\u00c9lite\u2019 juntos?|website=[[La Vanguardia]]|language=es|date=22 January 2020|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> The day after, the singer posted a video of her listening to the song on her Instagram Stories.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cuore.es/entretenimiento/rosalia-nueva-cancion-juro-que|title=Rosal\u00eda 'jura que' tiene nueva canci\u00f3n|last=M\u00e1rquez|first=Ana|website=[[Cuore (magazine)|Cuore]]|language=es|date=23 January 2020|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref> A couple hours after it, she announced that the song would be released on streaming platforms that same day. An hour before the official release, \"Juro Que\" leaked on [[Shazam (application)|Shazam]] and [[Apple Music]].\n\n==Critical reception==\nWiting for ''[[Los 40]]'', Laura Coca made the following statement about the song: \"the Spanish guitar and palmas share protagonism with the imposing voice of Rosal\u00eda. There's a lot of sentiment in every note. Embracing old melodies similar to the ones used in \"Que No Salga la Luna\" and \"Di Mi Nombre\", I am sure that this new single of her will become another chart-topper single\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://los40.com/los40/2020/01/23/musica/1579793358_803637.html|title=As\u00ed suena \u2018Juro Que\u2019, lo nuevo de Rosal\u00eda|last=Coca|first=Laura|website=Los 40|language=es|date=23 January 2020|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Music video ==\nThe music video for \"Juro Que\" was uploaded to [[YouTube]] on January 23, 2020. It stars Rosal\u00eda and Spanish-Moroccan actor Omar Ayuso. Rosal\u00eda plays the role of a woman whose lover has been imprisoned for over four hundred days. She promises loyalty to him and that she'll do whatever is in her hands to free him. The whole video consists of both of them interacting during a ''[[Conjugal visit|t\u00eate-\u00e0-t\u00eate]]''. The video was directed by Tanu Muino and produced by Montse Urniza. It was filmed in [[Barcelona]] in fall 2019.\n\nIt received over 5 milion views on YouTube in 24 hours.\n\n== Connection with ''El mal querer'' ==\nThe song as well as its music video could be related to the singer's 2018 project ''[[El mal querer]]''. The album illustrates and tells the story of Flamenca, the main character of the ''[[Romance of Flamenca]]'', a 13th-century Occitan novel. In the novel, Flamenca gets married to her all-time lover. Her husband is very jealous of her and is afraid that another man gets interested in his wife. His worst dreams come true since Flamenca begins a relationship with another man because she feels prisoned and cautive in her relationship with her husband. When the husband finds it out, he locks her up in a tower for the rest of her life. In the end, Flamenca gets liberated and kills her husband. When the police asks for the responsible, Flamenca's lover turns himself in and accepts the charges even though he isn't the guilty. ''El mal querer'' was released on November 2, 2018. It has been 447 days since its release. This connects with the first lyric of the song which says: \"my man has been imprisoned for more than 400 days\". Thus, this song could be a follow to her 2018 project; a song that continues Flamenca's story.\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]\n{{Unbulleted list|'''Recording and production'''}}\n* [[Rosal\u00eda (singer)|Rosal\u00eda Vila]] \u2013 vocals, songwriting, production, arrangement\n* [[El Guincho|Pablo D\u00edaz-Reixa]] \u2013 production, arrangement, recording engineering\n* Traditional \u2013 composer\n* Daniel Gomez Carrero \u2013 songwriting\n* Jos\u00e9 David Acedo Morales \u2013 arrangement\n* DJ Riggins \u2013 assistant engineering\n* Jacob Richards \u2013 assistant engineering\n* Mike Seaberg \u2013 assistant engineering\n* Chris Athens \u2013 master engineering\n* Jaycen Joshua \u2013 mixing engineering\n* Morning Estrada \u2013 recording engineering\n{{Unbulleted list|'''Additional musicians'''}}\n* Ane Jes\u00fas Carrasco Molina \u2013 choir vocal, clapping\n* Anna Colom \u2013 choir vocal\n* Claudia G\u00f3mez \u2013 choir vocal\n* Jose Alvaro Iba\u00f1ez \u2013 choir vocal, clapping\n* Jos\u00e9 Manuel Fernandez (Tobalo) \u2013 choir vocal, clapping\n* Juan Carlos Gil \u2013 choir vocal, clapping\n* Macario Iba\u00f1ez \u2013 choir vocal, clapping\n* Miguel Tellez \u2013 choir vocal, clapping\n* Joselito Acedo \u2013 guitar\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|PROMUSICAE]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.elportaldemusica.es/lists/top-100-canciones/2020/5|title=Top 100 Canciones: Semana 5|publisher=[[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a]]|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n| 7\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardlatinsongs|41|artist=Rosalia|rowheader=true|accessdate=5 February 2020}}\n|}\n\n==Release history==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Region\n! scope=\"col\"| Date\n! scope=\"col\"| Format\n! scope=\"col\"| Label\n! scope=\"col\"| {{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Various\n| 23 January 2020\n| {{hlist|[